 1209","1180":"1180","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Towie, Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marshal","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marshall","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Marshal was born in 1189, in Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland. She married Roger de Berkeley V Laird of Towie about 1209, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She died in 1228, in her hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1189–1228":"1189–1228","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1298":"1298","1285":"1285","1185":"1185","ABT 1209":"umbes 1209","1180":"1180","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Towie, Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1189–1228":"1189–1228","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1298":"1298","1285":"1285","1185":"1185","ABT 1209":"noin 1209","1180":"1180","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Towie, Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1189–1228":"1189–1228","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1298":"1298","1285":"1285","1185":"1185","ABT 1209":"environ 1209","1180":"1180","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","Towie, Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Margaret de Marshal est née en 1189, à Cullen, Banffshire, Écosse. Elle a épousé Roger de Berkeley V Laird of Towie environ 1209, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Elle est décédée en 1228, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 39 ans."},"de":{"1189–1228":"1189–1228","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1226":"12